bioghist.head: Biographical / Historical
bioghist.p: Lawrence Zelic Freedman was a forensic psychiatrist and a leading authority on the psychiatry of aggression, violence, crime, terrorism, and the interactions between psychiatry and the law. He was born on September 4, 1919 in Gardner, Massachusetts, the youngest of six brothers. He studied at Tufts University, where he earned a B.S. in 1940 and an M.D. in 1944. From 1942 to 1946 he served in the United States Navy, rising to the rank of Lieutenant. During this time he also completed his residency training in psychiatry at Yale Medical School. While in the Navy during World War II, Freedman was assigned to care for American serviceman imprisoned in military prisons, as well as German prisoners of war. These experiences stimulated his interest in the psychiatry of violence.

Freedman joined the Yale faculty in 1949 as an instructor in psychiatry and mental hygiene. He rose to the rank of assistant professor in 1951 and associate professor in 1954. He spent 1958 as a research associate at Cambridge University, and was a research fellow in the Center for Advanced Study in the Behavioral Sciences at Stanford University from 1959 to 1960. In 1961, Freedman was appointed the Foundations Fund Research Professor of Psychiatry at the University of Chicago, where he remained for the rest of his career.

Freedman's research interests were tied together by the common theme of applying psychiatric and psychoanalytic approaches to emerging social, legal, political, and behavioral topics. Throughout his career he conducted research studies on a variety of topics, including natural childbirth, human sexual behavior, criminal behavior, juvenile delinquency, terrorism, and political assassination, among others. He was also interested in using the tools of psychology and psychiatry to serve the common good. Freedman helped draft the Model Penal Code, which was adopted by the American Law Institute in 1962 to help state legislatures update their criminal codes. He also served on President Lyndon Johnson's National Commission on the Causes and Prevention of Violence, and developed a profile of potential presidential assassins at the request of the U.S. Secret Service. In the mid-1960s, Freedman became interested in the study of serial and mass murder. He conducted interviews with serial murderers John Wayne Gacy and Jeffrey Dahmer, as well as mass murderer Simon Peter Nelson, and testified at each of their criminal trials.

Freedman was the author of over 100 publications and served as a consultant to many local, national, and international organizations concerned with violence, crime, and psychiatry. Following his retirement from the University of Chicago, he maintained a private practice in psychoanalysis. Lawrence Z. Freedman died of a stroke at his home in Chicago on October 6, 2004.

processinfo.head: Processing Information
processinfo.p: The groupings of files into series and subseries in the papers generally reflects Freedman's original filing system, though in some cases files within these groupings were arranged alphabetically or chronologically by the archivists. Similarly, the majority of folder titles in the papers are the original titles that Freedman assigned to his files.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: The papers are arranged in six series: I. Research files, 1946–1988; II. Private psychiatric practice, 1948–1993; III. Conferences, lectures, seminars, and classes, 1948-1992; IV. Correspondence, general, 1946–1997; V. Subject files, 1938–1992; VI. Writings, 1938–1990.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The collection comprises the papers of forensic psychiatrist and former Yale professor, Lawrence Z. Freedman, and dates from 1938 to 1997. The papers are notable for documenting Freedman's significant contributions to the field of forensic psychiatry, as well as his studies of aggression, violence, crime, terrorism, and the interactions between psychiatry and the law. The bulk of the papers document Freedman's numerous research studies. While the most significant of Freedman's studies concerned the topics of deviancy, delinquency, criminality, and violence, he also conducted studies on other topics such as sleep and dreams, human sexual behavior, the effects of recreational drugs on communication, creativity, and obstetrics, among others. The most extensively documented study in the papers is the Sexuality, Violence, and Avarice Study (SVA), conducted by the Yale Unit in Psychiatry and the Law under Freedman's leadership between 1953 and 1957. The study, which used 1262 inmates from the Wethersfield State Prison as research subjects, sought to delineate the characteristics of different types of criminal defenders, gain further understanding of criminal behavior, and develop specific therapeutic treatments for offenders. Materials documenting this study include individual files on the inmates who participated; audio recordings and notes from therapy and interview sessions; project manuals; writings; and subject files. The papers also include significant documentation of Freedman's research into the psychology of terrorism, assassination, and political violence in the form of research materials and writings.

In addition to his research, the papers document Freedman's private psychiatric practice, as well as his work as a consultant. Materials documenting Freedman's psychiatric practice, which include patient files and audio recordings of therapy sessions, demonstrate the degree to which his research and clinical practice intersected and likely influenced each other. In particular, the patient files show that Freedman primarily treated individuals who had histories of violent or criminal behavior. As a consultant, Freedman often worked as an expert witness in criminal trials involving murder or other violent offenses. Materials documenting this work primarily consist of audio recordings and transcripts of forensic interviews conducted by Freedman, as well as notes, copies of medical records, and correspondence. Freedman also consulted on the drafting of the model penal code during the early 1960s. Materials related to this work include drafts of different sections of the code, correspondence, and meeting notes.

Lastly, the papers include a general assortment of Freedman's writings and correspondence, as well as materials related to conference presentations, lectures he delivered, and classes he taught. The papers provide virtually no insight into Freedman's personal life, and very little documentation of his life before his psychiatric and academic careers. The general writings, which include student papers dating from his freshman year at Tufts University, provide the only documentation of Freedman's early life.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Series I consists of papers related to research studies conducted by Lawrence Z. Freedman over the course of his academic career. The majority of materials in the series relate to Freedman's Sexuality, Violence, and Avarice (SVA) research project, as well as his studies of terrorism, assassination, and political violence. Also included are studies related to sleep and dreams, human sexual behavior, the effects of recreational drugs on communication, juvenile delinquency, creativity, obstetrics, and psychiatry and the law. In many instances, the topics of these individual studies intersect with one another. In particular, Freedman's interest in deviancy, delinquency, criminality, and violence are themes that thread through many of his research projects.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Freedman's sleep and dream study was conducted by Freedman at the University of Chicago in the early 1960s. The study involved the analysis and comparison of dreams between two groups of "deviant" and "delinquent" young men of different socioeconomic backgrounds. Materials documenting this work consist of background research materials, as well as descriptions of the study, data compiled from the study, notes, audio recordings of subject interviews, and correspondence.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Freedman's study on human sexual behavior dates from his tenure at Yale during the early 1950s, and was conducted in collaboration with Frank Beach. The study concerned the "sexual behavior, affects, attitudes, and phantasies [sic] in a sample of spouse pairs." Specifically, Freedman and Beach focused on approximately 10 to 15 young, college educated couples as their subjects, with intentions of conducting comparable studies with couples of different socioeconomic backgrounds. During the study, each individual subject filled out a paper questionnaire on his or her personal background and sexual experience, which was followed by an in-depth interview. The materials documenting this study include background research materials, correspondence, questionnaires, interview transcripts, and drafts of a manuscript titled, "Sex, Aggression, and Anxiety in the Human Subject," which reported on the findings of Freedman and Beach's research. It is not known whether this manuscript was ever published.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Materials related to the PIPC and POPC study date from the late 1940s and early 1950s, and consist primarily of case histories of study subjects on typewritten index cards, as well as charts featuring collated data from the study. All of the subjects of this study had been diagnosed with various depressive, neurotic, or psychotic conditions, and had been treated in either inpatient or outpatient psychiatric clinics. The subject case histories are organized according to the type of clinic at which a subject received treatment.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Freedman conducted two major studies of juvenile delinquency; one during the early 1950s while he was at Yale, and the other during the early 1960s at the University of Chicago. As with some of his other studies, the papers provide scant explanation of the purpose and general nature off the study he conducted at Yale. Materials documenting it consist primarily of data compiled from the Hartford and New Haven state juvenile courts, psychological evaluations of juvenile offenders conducted by state-employed clinicians, as well as some that appear to have been conducted by Freedman and his research staff. Box 14 includes some data from the state juvenile court in Hartford dating from 1965, but it is unclear whether these materials have any relation to the 1950s study. There are also some correspondence and background research materials pertaining to this study. The Chicago study involved Freedman and a number of other colleagues at the University of Chicago. Its purpose was to develop a delinquency control training center at the university. The purpose of the center was to provide training to practitioners who work in fields related to delinquency control, and then to study the ways that the training impacted the professional work of those practitioners. Materials documenting this study include a grant proposal describing its purpose and method (in box 17, folder 1), court files, background research materials, and correspondence. Lastly, box 14, folder 4 includes materials that suggest Freedman had considered applying some of the concepts developed during his SVA study to the juvenile offenders. However, it is not known whether this project ever came to fruition.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The Sexuality, Violence, and Avarice (SVA) study was conducted by the Yale Study Unit in Psychiatry and Law between 1953 and 1957. Freedman, along with three other psychiatrists, two psychologists, and a sociologist, carried out the project using inmates from the Wethersfield State Prison as their research subjects. Under the auspices of the study, the inmates were categorized into three groups based on the nature of the offense that resulted in their incarceration: sexuality for crimes of a sexual nature; violence for crimes that involved physical aggression; and avarice for crimes that involved theft. The overriding hypothesis of the study was that these three types of offenders differ from each other in terms of personality, social dynamics, and genetics. The study's purpose was to delineate the characteristics of the three types of offenders, gain further understanding of criminal behavior, and develop specific therapeutic treatment approaches for offenders. Over the course of the project, 1262 inmates were involved with it. Methods used over throughout the study included group psychological tests, group therapy sessions, pre-parole interviews, individual psychiatric consultations, and individual diagnostic testing.

Materials documenting the SVA study include writings; subject files; data collected over the course of the project; individual files on inmates who participated in the study; project manuals; notes on group therapy sessions; and audio recordings of some group therapy sessions. The project manuals in box 164 provide the most comprehensive explanation of the study's background, purpose, and methods, particularly the researchers' data collection, coding, and analysis procedures. The writings consist of multiple manuscripts related to the SVA study that Freedman worked on between the 1960s and 1980s. It seems that none of these manuscripts were ever published, and it is unclear if any of them are complete. The largest body of documents related to the SVA study are the individual prison inmate files, which are identified by the inmate's name and identification number. Each inmate's file contains a variety of documents, including biographical information, criminal records, psychological profiles, therapy session and interview notes, and psychological test results.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Freedman's Cree Indian study was conducted during the early 1960s in Attawapiskat, a community of Cree Indians in northern Ontario, Canada. At the time of the study, the community had about 400 members. The purpose of the study was to gather and analyze data about sexually and aggressively deviant behavior within the community, as well as existing legal and social controls over such behavior. It seems that Freedman was interested in studying the community due to its geographic isolation, its unique cultural mores, as well as its decentralized governance and social structure. Materials documenting the study include background information on the community, data gathered during the study, and notes on interviews with community members.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Freedman's Macacque study was conducted during the early 1950s, though the papers documenting the study date as late as the 1970s. The purpose of the project was to study the sexual behavior of Macacq monkeys, as well as the impact of aggressive behavior and anxiety on sexual behavior. The study was carried out using four male and four female Macacqs, successively paired with each other to make sixteen couplings. Their behavior was studied for two years in a laboratory setting. Materials documenting the study include correspondence, observation notes, writings, and background research material.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Freedman's creativity and career choice study was conducted from the late 1940s until at least the early 1970s, but the papers documenting it date primarily from the late 1950s through the mid-1960s. The purpose of the project was to study the relationship between creativity (generally defined as the ability interpret information in novel and unconventional ways, and the willingness to take risks) and career choice through psychoanalytic observation. Over the course of study, Freedman worked with approximately 50 individuals in a variety of occupations, including artists, writers, lawyers, doctors, scientists, teachers, politicians, and students. Each participant was subject to about 150 hours of analysis. Papers documenting the study include transcripts and audio recordings of therapy sessions, and writings.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The exact dates of Freedman's obstetrics study are unclear, but materials in the collection documenting it date primarily from the 1960s. The purpose of the study was to observe the ways that the interaction of roles and methods of communication between laboring mothers, their spouses, doctors, and nurses had on the mother's levels of fear and pain during childbirth. Though the exact methods employed during the study are not clearly documented, it seems that interviews with mothers about their childbirth experiences, as well as with their spouses and medical providers, were the primary means of gathering research data. Materials documenting the study include correspondence, research data (including interview notes), audio recordings of interviews, forms used during the study, and subject files.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Materials in this subseries primarily document the development and work of the Yale Study Unit in Psychiatry and the Law, which Freedman was heavily involved with. The Study Unit was conceived and established in 1953 as a semi-autonomous, interdisciplinary unit co-administered by the Department of Psychiatry in the Yale Medical School, and the Yale Law School. Its primary purpose conduct research in the area of deviant behavior and its intersection with social and legal processes. The Study Unit was staffed with psychiatric, sociological and legal professionals, with Freedman as its first chairman. Its work was divided into three areas: research, consultation, and teaching. Materials in the subseries include papers documenting the Study Unit's founding and early years (primarily located in box 312), and conferences, seminars, and sponsored by the Study Unit. It also includes materials related more generally to Freedman's interest in the topic of psychiatry and the law, including correspondence, subject files and writings.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Freedman's study of terrorism, assassination, and political violence began in the 1970s and continued for much of the rest of his life. The focus of his research was twofold: first, what are the psychological, social, and cultural factors that compel people to become terrorists, and second, why do terroristic acts evoke widespread fear and panic in the public? Unlike the other research projects documented in the collection, this one was primarily academic in nature, and did not involve any clinical experiments. The groups and individuals that Freedman studied as terrorists included inner city criminal gangs; middle eastern nationalist groups; leftist militant groups in the United States; and assassins of political leaders. Freedman was a prolific writer on the topic of terrorism, having authored a number of articles and edited several books, and the majority of papers documenting this study consist of his writings. Also included are clippings, subject files, conference presentations, and transcripts of interviews with Freedman.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Materials in this series document Lawrence Z. Freedman's private practice, which he maintained throughout his career. In his private practice, Freedman provided psychoanalysis services to individual patients, and served as a consultant in a variety of capacities, including as an expert witness in criminal trials, as well as for public service projects, such as the drafting of the Model Penal Code. Materials documenting his psychoanalysis services include individual patient files, which typically consist of therapy session notes, psychological profiles and diagnostic reports, and occasionally legal records such as arrest and court records. There are also audio recordings of therapy sessions with several patients. There is also a grouping of patient records that are identified according to the patient's diagnosis, or a criminal offense committed by the patient that necessitated psychiatric treatment or psychological evaluation. These files generally contain the same types of documents as the individual patient files.

Materials related to Freedman's work as an expert witness consultant include transcripts and audio recordings of forensic interview sessions, background research materials, copies of medical records, notes, and correspondence. Lastly, papers related to Freedman's work on the Model Penal Code include multiple drafts of different sections of the code, correspondence between Freedman and others who worked on the project, and notes from meetings of the group that collaborated on the drafting of the code.

scopecontent.p: This series comprises a small assortment of both incoming and outgoing correspondence spanning Freedman's entire career, though the bulk of materials date from the 1950s through the 1990s. The series includes a small section of chronologically arranged correspondence, as well as correspondence arranged by topic or the correspondent's name.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series comprises papers and articles written by Lawrence Z. Freedman, dating from his years as an undergraduate student at Tufts University in the late 1930s through the early 1990s. It includes both typewritten manuscripts and reprints of previously published works. The writings touch upon most all of Freedman's research interests throughout his career, and the papers dating from his undergraduate and medical school years represent the collection's only substantial documentation of Freedman's education.
